review_blob: Strong smell of rosemary and sage, but it did not taste like a liquid her garden.  The herbs blended very nicely with the hops for a very dry-hoppy ale.  A nice collaboration between the best chefs and brewers in the area.

Just had the Stone batch.  Great head retention with a nice golden color that was slightly hazy.  Had a strong sage smell to it, but not too spicy going down, very smooth and dry.  I finished my glass without even realizing it; the hallmark of a great beer.
beer_name: Stone / Dogfish Head / Victory Saison du BUFF

review_blob: Great Belgian wheat.  Light and summery with coriander and orange peels.  I know if youre a beer purist you might cringe at this, but squeeze a little blood orange into this beer is amazing.
Did not like this beer.  Dark amber in color but no punch.  It just tasted like liquid smoked hickory bacon to me.
A wheat beer with a summer kick.  Spicy and fruity at the beginning with a nice smooth unfiltered end.
One of my favorites.  Amber caramel color with a sweet malty start that finishes with a  lingering bitterness.
Dont usually like the light beers, but this one has taste and is refreshing.  If you get it at victory, they serve it in a special traditional style glass.

A belgian tripel that you would think comes from belgium.  Light spice and hops. Some sweeter alcohol in very end. Light belgian yeast aroma. Very drinkable, you will get drunk fast if this is all youre drinking.
Pours a dark amber with aroma and taste of malt and hops.  Smooth, slightly dry finish, closest thing I have had to the style over in the states.  Frequently see Ron and Bill drinking it.
Light amber color with small fleet white head.  Very standard for the style, like sweetness to it.  Prefer the Abby 6 or 8.

Im sorry, I did not like this.  Had it off the firkin at TJs and it just tasted like salt water with a hint of fruitiness to it.  I really wanted to like it.  It smelled earthy and bad, and it just was not pleasurable.

Had this off the firkin at TJs.  It smells like a hefeweizen, and actually tasted fruity to me at first.  As I took more sips,  I got more of the rye taste and floral notes that I was expecting.  Very light in color and very smooth in taste.  I liked it!
A little hard to drink, had it off a firkin at TJs. Strong taste and smell of herbs and dough with a floral overtones.  There was just too much going on for me.

A light summer  golden ale with a hoppy kick at the end.  Its a good beer, that accomplishes its purpose. Its a beer for the masses and Id happily drink it outside during Philly Beer Week.  Its a great beer to introduce to those who have yet to enter the micro brew world; they will never turn back after drinking it.

Very smooth and light as its in your mouth with caramel and hoppy notes.  The bitterness of this ESB doesnt hit until its down your throat and thats really how this style should be.  Reminds me a lot of Victorys ESB in color and taste which I guess makes sense since they were a collaborator.

Was able to drink this at TJs on draft thanks to a knowledgeable server. It smells of chocolate, sour cherry, and funk. It tastes of milk chocolate and coffee, toast. A sour Belgian without any overwhelming sour notes. Body is light with good carbonation.

Massive, big beer.  The strongest, most intense beer I ever had.  I actually prefer this beer off the hand pump.  It makes the beer smoother and youre able to taste more subtle flavors rather than just the intense hoppy and malty  flavors

Very good for the style. Thick body, smooth taste with hints of chocolate and espresso.  On nitrogen so it has a creamy head that last until the last drop.  Less bitter than guiness so you can really make out more of the subtle tastes of the style.  If you see this on tap somewhere I would get it.
Crisp, smooth pilsner.  Usually alters between different hops, tettnang, spalt, hallertauer, and saaz.  Right now theyre making it with a French hop called Strissle and spalt select.
Hard to believe this is a lager, but alas it is.  Very smooth with chocolate and espresso taste.  Very drinkable, very unique style.

You can smell the Brettanomyces, but they blend into the beer so there isnt much sourness to the beer.  The malted rye is very much at the front of the beer, but then blends in nicely with the hops to create a rich, earthy character.

I overheard a Bells brewer at City Tap House for Philly Beer Week that he thought it came out too spicy, but I thought it was just weird.  The wild yeasts werent that overwhelming, they gave the beer that nice sour smell that I like, but there was just an odd flavor to it that I wasnt liking all that much.  If I see it on tap again, I will definitely give it another shot.

I was surprised by the brownish tan color, it was lighter than I expected for a barleywine, but the taste was a nice spicy caramel taste.  There were layers of different tastes as it sat in your mouth and hit different points as it was going down.
This beer almost had the texture of liquid molasses, that may not sound appealing but it was amazing.  Its aged for months in bourbon barrels which brings out the strong vanilla and coconut flavors.
beer_name: Bells Hell Hath No Fury - Bourbon Barrel

review_blob: Incredibly dark and thick with an immensely complex flavor profile.  Brewed specifically for vintage aging in mind.

Referred to at the Black Note during Philly Beer week, this beer is aged in freshly used bourbon barrels for anywhere from 6-18 months.  Unlike most beers that age in bourbon barrels that have a distinct bourbon taste, this one  blends together perfectly.  Malt:  chocolate, coffee.
A great starter beer for a new brewery and perfect for the upcoming summer months.  An unfiltered look with a light hoppy taste at the end.  Its refreshing with some floral notes to it.
